{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-aaec2511c67e538d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tAudio Sentiment Analysis via Distillation and Cross-Modal Integration of\n2\tGenerated Multilingual Transcripts\n3\tAndrei-George Durduna , Victor Constantinescub , Radu Tudor Ionescua,b,∗\n4\ta Department of Computer Science, University of Bucharest, 15G Iuliu Maniu, Bucharest 061075, Romania\n5\tb Department of Data Science, PPC Romania, 30 Mircea Voda, Bucharest 030667, Romania\n6\t\n7\tarXiv:2607.06611v1 [cs.CL] 7 Jul 2026\n8\t\n9\tAbstract\n10\tAutomatically recognizing the sentiment, positive or negative, from speech is a challenging task, requiring both the\n11\tanalysis of vocal inflections and the interpretation of uttered words. Recent solutions rely on audio foundation models\n12\tto solve the task, but it remains unclear if such models can take all aspects into account. To this end, we propose a\n13\tmultimodal solution that integrates audio and text information via cross-modal transformers, where text transcripts\n14\tare automatically generated via an automatic speech recognition (ASR) tool. Moreover, we create multiple text\n15\tmodalities by automatically translating the transcripts into multiple languages via machine translation tools. Audio\n16\tand multilingual text features are combined via a cascaded architecture comprising cross-modal transformer blocks\n17\tthat integrate modalities one by one. We further distill knowledge from the multimodal model, called teacher, into\n18\ta unimodal (audio only) model, called student. We conduct experiments on a large-scale dataset, demonstrating that\n19\tthe automatically generated textual information can bring significant performance boosts in multimodal sentiment\n20\tpolarity classification. Our ablation study confirms that both automatic transcripts and automatic translations are\n21\thelpful. Moreover, we show that the audio-only model can be enhanced via distillation, boosting performance without\n22\tany computational overhead during inference. To reproduce the reported results, we publicly release our code at\n23\thttps://github.com/andreidurdun/cross-modal-audio-sentiment.\n24\tKeywords: multimodal learning; audio sentiment analysis; audio polarity classification; cross-modal transformer\n25\t\n26\t1. Introduction\n27\tSentiment polarity classification from speech is an actively studied task [2, 11, 28, 31, 44], having a broad range of\n28\treal-world applications, such as customer service call analysis [5], virtual assistant adaptation [1], mental health monitoring [42], vehicle driver monitoring [52] and gaming experience adaptation [25], among others. As for most speech\n29\tprocessing tasks nowadays, deep learning models [14, 18, 37, 41], especially audio foundation models [3, 9, 37, 38],\n30\trepresent the mainstream solution for polarity classification, due to their typically high accuracy levels. However, the\n31\ttask remains challenging, as it involves the concurrent analysis of several aspects, including tone (which transmits\n32\temotion), pitch (which conveys excitement or calmness), word usage (which reflects the polarity of the transmitted\n33\tmessage), irony / sarcasm (which may often indicate the opposite opinion than the transmitted message). Disentangling these aspects is a key pathway towards improving performance, yet this area remains largely underexplored in\n34\tcurrent literature.\n35\tTo this end, we propose a novel knowledge distillation (KD) pipeline [15], where the teacher model benefits from\n36\tdisentangled audio and text information. While the audio modality is readily available, the text transcript is not directly\n37\t∗ Corresponding author.\n38\t\n39\tE-mail address: radu.ionescu@fmi.unibuc.ro\n40\t\n41\tPreprint submitted to Elsevier\n42\t\n43\tJuly 9, 2026\n44\t\n45\t\fAudio modality\n46\t\n47\t..\n48\t\n49\t..\n50\t\n51\tWavLM\n52\tStudent\n53\t\n54\tClassi'(ation\n55\tHead\n56\tKnowledge\n57\tdistillation\n58\t\n59\tTea(her\n60\t\n61\tClassi'(ation\n62\tHead\n63\tCross-Modal\n64\tTransformer\n65\tAudio modality\n66\t\n67\t..\n68\t\n69\t..\n70\t\n71\tWavLM\n72\t\n73\tCross-Modal\n74\tTransformer\n75\t\n76\tText modality [En]\n77\tI\n78\tlove\n79\t\n80\t[CLS]\n81\t\n82\t..\n83\t\n84\t[CLS]\n85\t\n86\tMe\n87\ten(anta\n88\t\n89\tdog\n90\t\n91\tRoBERTuito\n92\t\n93\tCross-Modal\n94\tTransformer\n95\t\n96\t..\n97\t\n98\tAutomati( Spee(h\n99\tRe(ognition\n100\t\n101\tText modality [Es]\n102\t\n103\t..\n104\t\n105\t..\n106\t\n107\tperro\n108\t\n109\tJ’\n110\tadore\n111\t\n112\tText modality [Fr]\n113\t\n114\tCamemBERT\n115\t\n116\t..\n117\t\n118\tNLLB-200\n119\tNeural Ma(hine\n120\tTranslation\n121\t\n122\tCross-Modal\n123\tTransformer\n124\t\n125\t..\n126\t\n127\t[CLS]\n128\t\n129\t(hien\n130\t[CLS]\n131\t\n132\tI(h\n133\t\n134\tGBERT\n135\t\n136\t..\n137\t\n138\tliebe\n139\t\n140\tText modality [De]\n141\t\n142\t..\n143\t\n144\tFaster\n145\tWhisper\n146\t\n147\tRoBERTa\n148\t\n149\tHund\n150\t\n151\tFigure 1: The proposed pipeline based on learning under privileged information, which distills information from a multimodal (audio-text) teacher\n152\tmodel into a unimodal (audio only) student model. The teacher model comprises frozen ASR and NMT models to generate text transcripts and\n153\ttranslations, respectively. Trainable models process the generated texts to extract latent representations that are further integrated via cross-modal\n154\ttransformer blocks. Best viewed in color.\n155\t\n156\taccessible in real-world scenarios. We therefore employ an automatic speech recognition (ASR) model to generate text\n157\ttranscripts. However, ASR technology is not perfect, and consequently, the transcripts may be affected by recognition\n158\terrors. Moreover, language-specific pre-trained models, e.g. BERT [10], may be affected by training dataset biases.\n159\tTo mitigate biases of language-specific models, we further propose to employ a neural machine translation (NMT)\n160\tsystem to automatically translate ASR transcripts into multiple languages, namely German (DE), French (FR) and\n161\tSpanish (ES). The resulting text modalities along with the original audio modality are integrated into a unified model\n162\tbased on cascaded cross-modal transformer blocks, as illustrated in Figure 1. Each cross-modal transformer integrates\n163\tone modality with the upstream information, until all modalities are combined into the joint model.\n164\tWhile the ASR and NMT models provide the means to disentangle voice and message information, they also\n165\trepresent a processing bottleneck, i.e. generating the text transcripts and translations requires extra computational\n166\tresources and processing time. The processing speed is of utter importance for applications requiring real-time sentiment polarity assessment, such as virtual assistant adaptation and vehicle driver monitoring. To harness the multimodal information while preserving the processing time of the unimodal (audio only) model, we employ learning\n167\tunder privileged information (LUPI) [26, 30, 47], a knowledge distillation (KD) pipeline that transfers knowledge\n168\tlearned by a teacher model having access to extra data representations (in our case, the generated text modalities) to a\n169\tstudent model which can only access the original representation (in our case, the audio modality). The main advantage of this distillation framework is that the extra modalities are not needed during inference. This means that the\n170\tASR, the NMT and the multiple text embedding models are only used at training time. The resulting student model\n171\t2\n172\t\n173\t\frepresents an effective and scalable solution for audio sentiment classification.\n174\tIn summary, our framework relies on two assumptions: (i) generated transcripts and translations provide additional\n175\tsentiment polarity clues that can be effectively harnessed by a multimodal model; (ii) knowledge from the heavy\n176\tmultimodal teacher model can be distilled into an efficient unimodal student. To validate the two hypotheses, we\n177\tconduct experiments on the large-scale MSP-Podcast corpus [7]. Our experiments show that integrating generated\n178\tmultimodal information leads to significant performance gains, up to +5.89% in terms of macro-F1 and +5.15% in\n179\tterms of accuracy, confirming hypothesis (i). Moreover, distilling knowledge from the multimodal teacher into the\n180\taudio-only student boosts the performance of the student by +1.54% in terms of macro-F1 and +0.81% in terms of\n181\taccuracy, thus validating hypothesis (ii). Furthermore, we show ablation results justifying the utility of both text\n182\ttranscripts and translations.\n183\tIn summary, our contribution is twofold:\n184\t• We propose a novel knowledge distillation pipeline for audio sentiment classification, which harnesses both\n185\tgenerated text transcripts and translations via a cascaded cross-modal transformer architecture able to effectively\n186\tintegrate multiple modalities.\n187\t• We perform experiments showing that generated text modalities lead to considerable performance gains, and\n188\tthat knowledge from a multimodal teacher model can be effectively transferred to an efficient unimodal student.\n189\t2. Related Work\n190\tSentiment/emotion recognition from speech. Sentiment polarity classification from speech [2, 11, 28, 31, 44],\n191\ta.k.a. audio sentiment analysis, is the task of automatically determining the polarity of the sentiment verbally expressed by a person, where typical options are positive, neutral and negative. The task is deeply connected to speech\n192\temotion recognition (SER) [12, 24], where the aim is to precisely establish the emotion class, e.g. happy, anger or\n193\tfear, going beyond polarity classification. Both tasks have evolved from hand-crafted acoustic features and conventional classifiers towards end-to-end deep models operating directly on raw waveforms [12, 24]. Early deep learning\n194\tsolutions relied on convolutional and recurrent architectures applied to spectrograms or Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients, with attention-based pooling becoming a common strategy for aggregating frame-level emotional cues into\n195\tutterance-level predictions [12]. More recently, the dominant paradigm has shifted towards large self-supervised\n196\tspeech foundation models, such as wav2vec 2.0 [3], HuBERT [16] and WavLM [9], which provide universal representations that transfer well to paralinguistic tasks. Wang et al. [48] benchmarked wav2vec 2.0 and HuBERT for SER,\n197\tspeaker verification and spoken language understanding, showing that fine-tuning self-supervised encoders consistently outperforms spectrogram-based baselines. WavLM, in particular, jointly models masked speech prediction and\n198\tdenoising, and has emerged as a strong backbone for SER in naturalistic conditions [7, 9].\n199\tProgress in naturalistic SER has been largely driven by the MSP-Podcast corpus [7], a large-scale collection of\n200\tspontaneous emotional speech that supports both categorical and attribute-based tasks. The INTERSPEECH 2025\n201\tSpeech Emotion Recognition Challenge [33] further confirmed the difficulty of the task in the wild: across 93 participating teams, top-performing systems combined audio foundation models with text-based features obtained via\n202\tautomatic speech recognition (ASR), highlighting the practical value of multimodal supervision when reference transcripts are unavailable. While these approaches achieve strong results, most submissions adopt heavy multimodal\n203\tinference pipelines, raising a natural question about whether part of this gain can be compressed back into audio-only\n204\tdeployments. Our work adopts MSP-Podcast and WavLM as the basis for an audio-centered pipeline, and directly\n205\ttargets this efficiency question via distillation.\n206\tMultimodal audio-text sentiment/emotion analysis. A complementary line of research jointly models acoustic and\n207\tlinguistic information, motivated by the observation that prosody and lexical content carry largely complementary\n208\taffective cues [24, 51]. Yoon et al. [51] proposed one of the early audio-text dual-encoder architectures for emotion\n209\trecognition, combining an RNN over acoustic features with a textual encoder. Tsai et al. [45] introduced the Multimodal Transformer (MulT), in which directional cross-modal attention aligns unaligned audio, text and visual streams,\n210\testablishing cross-modal attention as the mainstream fusion mechanism. Subsequent work has explored alternative\n211\tfusion strategies, including multi-scale locally aggregated descriptors [27], self-adjusting cross-modal representations\n212\tthat preserve unimodal characteristics [50], and hierarchical cross-modal attention with dual audio pathways [46].\n213\tRistea et al. [39, 40] further proposed a cascaded cross-modal transformer (CCMT) that fuses multiple textual views\n214\t3\n215\t\n216\t\fderived from different translations of the same utterance with the audio signal, which directly inspired the fusion\n217\tmodule used by our teacher.\n218\tA practical limitation of multimodal SER is that ground-truth transcripts are rarely available in real-world scenarios. Lakomkin et al. [20] showed that training and evaluating sentiment models with human-transcribed text leads to\n219\tan optimistic estimate of performance, and argued for end-to-end integration with ASR. Shon et al. [43] subsequently\n220\tshowed that leveraging pre-trained language encoders on ASR transcripts can outperform traditional audio-only sentiment systems, despite recognition errors. Li et al. [22] benchmarked SER with ASR transcripts at varying word\n221\terror rates across multiple datasets, finding that SER is surprisingly tolerant to moderate ASR errors when appropriate\n222\tfusion and correction mechanisms are employed. Wu et al. [49] went one step further and used text-based emotional\n223\tdescriptions generated from non-textual modalities as an additional input to a cross-modal transformer. While these\n224\tworks confirm that automatically generated text is a useful signal for affect modeling, they still require the text branch\n225\tat inference time. In contrast, we use generated transcripts and translations strictly as privileged information during\n226\ttraining, and transfer the resulting knowledge into an audio-only student.\n227\tKnowledge distillation for speech and multimodal models. Knowledge distillation (KD) [15] is a model compression technique in which a small student network is trained to match the softened output distribution of a larger teacher,\n228\tthereby inheriting part of the teacher’s “dark knowledge”. A complementary perspective is given by the Learning Using Privileged Information (LUPI) paradigm of Vapnik et al. [47], where the teacher has access to additional data\n229\t(privileged information) that is unavailable at test time. Lopez-Paz et al. [26] unified these two perspectives under the\n230\tframework of generalized distillation, which directly motivates our choice of using automatically generated text as a\n231\ttraining-only privileged modality.\n232\tBuilding on these foundations, several recent works have applied KD specifically to multimodal emotion recognition. Georgescu et al. [13] applied a teacher-student distillation objective combining hard labels and softened teacher\n233\tpredictions in an affect recognition setting, which we adopt in our distillation stage. Li et al. [23] proposed Decoupled\n234\tMultimodal Distilling, which factorizes multimodal representations into modality-invariant and modality-exclusive\n235\tspaces before performing cross-modal distillation, improving robustness to modality gaps. Muaz et al. [32] explicitly targeted the setting where only speech is available at inference time, using a multi-modal teacher (audio, text\n236\tand video) to supervise an audio-only student via masked training and KD on IEMOCAP [6]. More recently, Li et\n237\tal. [21] introduced SUMMER, a heterogeneous multimodal integration framework that uses interactive KD between\n238\ta unimodal-driven teacher and a multimodal student to mitigate gradient conflicts in multimodal learning. Our work\n239\tdiffers from the above methods in two important ways. First, we specifically target sentiment polarity classification\n240\ton large-scale naturalistic speech (MSP-Podcast [7]), rather than acted or conversational corpora such as IEMOCAP\n241\t[6] and MELD [36]. Second, the privileged modalities in our teacher are not captured by additional sensors, but are\n242\tautomatically generated from the audio itself via ASR and machine translation, which makes the overall pipeline fully\n243\taudio-driven at inference time, while preserving the benefits of multimodal supervision during training.\n244\t3. Method\n245\tWe propose an audio-centered affect classification framework based on multimodal knowledge distillation. The\n246\tmain objective of this work is to train an efficient speech-only classifier that can benefit from multimodal information\n247\tduring training, while remaining efficient at inference time. To this end, we adopt a teacher-student strategy. The\n248\tteacher is a multimodal model that jointly processes acoustic and text-based information, whereas the student is an\n249\taudio-only WavLM [9] classifier. The student is optimized using both ground-truth labels and the soft predictions of\n250\tthe teacher, so that part of the multimodal knowledge can be transferred to a unimodal model.\n251\tMultimodal teacher model. The teacher model is built to integrate complementary information extracted from\n252\tspeech and text. For each audio sample, we first generate an English transcript using a Faster-Whisper [19] automatic\n253\tspeech recognition model. The English transcript is then translated with NLLB-200 [34] into additional languages\n254\tsupported by the framework, such as Spanish, German, and French. In this way, the system constructs several textual\n255\tmodalities of the same utterance, each potentially capturing different semantic nuances.\n256\tEach active modality is encoded with a dedicated pre-trained backbone. The acoustic branch relies on WavLMbase-plus [9], while the textual branches are modeled with language-specific transformer encoders: RoBERTa-base\n257\t[4] for English, RoBERTuito-base [35] for Spanish, GBERT-base [8] for German, and CamemBERT-base [29] for\n258\tFrench. These encoders produce fixed-dimensional embeddings, which are then projected into a common latent space\n259\t4\n260\t\n261\t\fby modality-specific adapters. Each adapter transforms the corresponding embedding into a fixed number of learnable\n262\tpatch tokens, ensuring that all modalities share the same token dimensionality and the same number of tokens.\n263\tThe tokens produced by all active modalities are concatenated and passed to a Cascaded Cross-Modal Transformer\n264\t(CCMT) [39]. To preserve modality identity, the model uses modality-specific positional embeddings. CCMT performs a sequence of cross-modal attention operations, progressively integrating acoustic and linguistic information.\n265\tEach cross-modal attention block combines two modalities. Formally, for any two modalities i and j, the output of\n266\tthe cross-attention layer, denoted as Oi+ j ∈ Rk×d , is computed as:\n267\t\n268\t\n269\t Qi · K ⊤j \n270\t\n271\t(1)\n272\tOi+ j = softmax  √  · V j ,\n273\td\n274\twhere Qi = T i ·WQ , K = T j ·WK , V = T j ·WV , and d represents the token dimension of the attention head. WQ , WK , WV\n275\trepresent learnable weights, while T i and T j represent the tokens coming from modalities i and j, respectively. The\n276\tcross-attention layer integrates query tokens from modality i with key and value tokens from modality j. The [CLS]\n277\ttoken from the final multimodal representation is fed into a classification head that outputs one of the three target\n278\tclasses: negative, neutral, or positive.\n279\tThe purpose of the teacher is twofold. First, it aims to achieve strong multimodal classification performance by\n280\tjointly exploiting speech and language information. Second, it provides informative soft targets for the student during\n281\tdistillation, enabling the final audio-only model to benefit from knowledge that is otherwise unavailable at inference\n282\ttime.\n283\tTeacher training. The teacher training pipeline is organized into two stages. In the first stage, each backbone is\n284\ttrained independently on the target sentiment classification task. The text encoders are trained on their corresponding\n285\ttextual inputs, while the WavLM model is trained directly on raw audio. This step allows each encoder to learn\n286\tmodality-specific discriminative features before multimodal fusion is performed. For each branch, the best checkpoint\n287\tis selected based on validation performance.\n288\tIn the second stage, the selected backbone checkpoints are reused as feature extractors for the multimodal model.\n289\tInstead of repeatedly forwarding raw inputs through all encoders during CCMT training, we first generate and cache\n290\tprecomputed embeddings for each dataset partition. This reduces the computational cost of multimodal training and\n291\tmakes it easier to compare multiple combinations of modalities under the same setting.\n292\tOnce the embeddings are available, each modality is passed through its dedicated adapter, which maps the unimodal representation to a sequence of patch tokens in a shared latent space. The token sequences are subsequently\n293\tfed into the CCMT. While training the multimodal fusion module based on CCMT, the backbone representations\n294\tremain fixed, through the use of precomputed embeddings. This strategy stabilizes optimization, since the fusion\n295\tmodel receives already informative unimodal features. It also accelerates training by removing repeated backbone\n296\tcomputations.\n297\tAfter training several multimodal configurations, the best-performing CCMT model is selected and frozen. This\n298\tmodel becomes the teacher network used in the distillation stage.\n299\tAudio-only student model. The student represents the final deployment model of the proposed framework. It consists\n300\tof a WavLM backbone followed by a lightweight classification head, and it receives only the raw audio waveform as\n301\tinput. Unlike the teacher, the student does not require transcription, translation, or multimodal fusion during inference,\n302\twhich makes it considerably more efficient. Although the student operates only on the acoustic modality, it is trained\n303\tto approximate both the hard labels and the behavior of the multimodal teacher. Therefore, the final student can\n304\tcompress part of the cross-modal knowledge of the teacher model into an audio-only model.\n305\tDistillation stage. The distillation stage is the core mechanism through which multimodal knowledge is transferred to\n306\tthe student [15]. Let zt and z s denote the logits produced by the teacher and student models, respectively. We compute\n307\tsoftened probability distributions using a temperature parameter τ:\n308\t\u0012z \u0013\n309\t\u0012z \u0013\n310\tt\n311\ts\n312\tpt = softmax\n313\t,\n314\tp s = softmax\n315\t.\n316\t(2)\n317\tτ\n318\tτ\n319\tThe student is trained with a combination of two objectives. The first objective is the standard cross-entropy loss with\n320\trespect to the ground-truth label y (given as a one-hot encoding):\n321\tk\n322\tX\n323\tLCE (y, p s ) = −\n324\tyi · log(p s,i ),\n325\t(3)\n326\ti=1\n327\t\n328\t5\n329\t\n330\t\fwhere k is the number of classes. The second objective is a distillation loss that encourages the student to match the\n331\tteacher’s softened output distribution:\n332\tLKD = τ2 · DKL (pt ∥ p s ),\n333\t\n334\t(4)\n335\t\n336\twhere DKL is the Kullback–Leibler (KL) divergence.\n337\tThe final training objective is given by:\n338\tL = (1 − λ) · LCE + λ · LKD ,\n339\t\n340\t(5)\n341\t\n342\twhere λ ∈ [0, 1] controls the balance between hard supervision and teacher guidance. Through this objective, the student learns not only the correct class assignments, but also the relative confidence structure encoded by the multimodal\n343\tteacher. This is particularly important in sentiment classification, where class boundaries may be ambiguous and soft\n344\tpredictions can convey useful information about inter-class similarity. As a result, the student can approximate part\n345\tof the richer decision process of the teacher, despite only having access to audio information.\n346\t4. Experiments\n347\tDataset. We conduct experiments on the large-scale MSP-Podcast corpus [7], a benchmark dataset for speech-based\n348\taffect analysis. The experiments follow the official corpus partitions, namely train (169,190 samples), development\n349\t(34,399 samples), and test-1 (46,294 samples), in order to ensure a consistent evaluation protocol.\n350\tFor the sentiment polarity classification task, the original emotion annotations are mapped to three target classes:\n351\tnegative, neutral, and positive. Negative emotions such as anger, sadness, disgust, contempt, and fear are grouped\n352\tinto the negative class, while happy and neutral samples are assigned to positive and neutral classes, respectively. The\n353\tremaining samples are assigned according to their valence score, with low-valence utterances mapped to negative, and\n354\thigh-valence utterances mapped to positive.\n355\tDuring preprocessing, all audio signals are resampled to 16 kHz, while transcript files are aligned at the utterance\n356\tlevel through the corresponding file identifiers. This setup enables both multimodal teacher training and audio-only\n357\tstudent evaluation within the same experimental framework.\n358\tImplementation details. In addition to the available audio recordings, we construct auxiliary textual modalities for\n359\tmultimodal training. Each utterance is first transcribed into English using an ASR model, and the resulting transcript is\n360\tthen translated into additional languages, namely Spanish, German, and French. Thus, each sample can be represented\n361\tby its acoustic signal together with one or more text-based views derived from speech.\n362\tOur experiments rely on a progressive three-step training setup. First, we independently fine-tune the text-only\n363\tclassifiers for each language (English, Spanish, German, and French), and a standard WavLM-base-plus audio baseline\n364\t(without KD). Second, we leverage these fine-tuned text and audio models as robust feature extractors to train the\n365\tmultimodal teacher model (CCMT). Finally, we establish our deployment-ready pipeline, where a fresh WavLMbase-plus student model learns from the fully-trained CCMT teacher via KD. We implemented all models in PyTorch,\n366\tutilizing mixed-precision training for the audio and multimodal networks to optimize memory and computational\n367\tefficiency.\n368\tHyperparameter setup. In Table 1, we report the main training and architectural hyperparameters for all models.\n369\tTo efficiently fine-tune the pre-trained unimodal models, and prevent them from forgetting their original knowledge,\n370\twe use Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) [17], while keeping the original pre-trained weights frozen. The text-only\n371\tclassifiers are trained via AdamW for 5 epochs with a batch size of 256, an initial learning rate of 2 · 10−4 , a LoRA\n372\trank (r) of 16, and a scaling factor (α) of 32, without gradient accumulation. Similarly, the WavLM audio baseline is\n373\tfine-tuned via AdamW for 5 epochs with a learning rate of 3 · 10−4 . The LoRA parameters are set to r = 8 and α = 16.\n374\tWavLM uses a physical batch size of 16 and two gradient accumulation steps.\n375\tFor the multimodal classification task, the Cascaded Cross-Modal Transformer (CCMT) fuses the linguistic and\n376\tacoustic representations extracted by the previously fine-tuned unimodal backbones. The CCMT is trained for up to\n377\t50 epochs with the AdamW optimizer and a linear warm-up scheduler. The initial learning rate is 10−4 , the batch\n378\tsize is 128, and gradient accumulation is turned off. To prevent overfitting, we use an early stopping mechanism that\n379\tmonitors the validation macro-F1 score and stops the training if the performance does not improve.\n380\tDuring the distillation stage, the WavLM student uses the same architecture and training parameters as the audio\n381\tbaseline. However, the student is trained using two combined objectives: the standard cross-entropy loss on the\n382\tground-truth labels and a KD loss based on the soft probabilities predicted by the teacher. We consider two teacher\n383\t6\n384\t\n385\t\fTable 1: Summary of training and architectural hyperparameters across model configurations.\n386\t\n387\tHyperparameter\n388\t\n389\tText Backbones\n390\t\n391\tWavLM Baseline & Student\n392\t\n393\tCCMT Teacher\n394\t\n395\tEpochs\n396\tLearning Rate\n397\tOptimizer\n398\tScheduler\n399\tBatch Size\n400\tGradient Accumulation\n401\tMixed Precision\n402\tLoRA Rank (r)\n403\tLoRA Alpha (α)\n404\t\n405\t5\n406\t2 · 10−4\n407\tAdamW\n408\tLinear Warmup\n409\t256\n410\t1\n411\tFalse\n412\t16\n413\t32\n414\t\n415\t5\n416\t3 · 10−4\n417\tAdamW\n418\tLinear Warmup\n419\t16\n420\t2\n421\tTrue\n422\t8\n423\t16\n424\t\n425\t50 (early stopping)\n426\t1 · 10−4\n427\tAdamW\n428\tLinear Warmup\n429\t128\n430\t1\n431\tTrue\n432\t-\n433\t\n434\t2.0\n435\t0.7\n436\t\n437\t-\n438\t\n439\tKnowledge distillation (student only):\n440\tTemperature (τ)\n441\tKD Weight (α)\n442\t\n443\t-\n444\t\n445\tTable 2: Performance of unimodal, multimodal and KD-based models on the MSP-Podcast corpus [7], alongside inference time in ms (measured\n446\ton one Nvidia RTX 4060 8GB GPU, using a batch size of 8).\n447\t\n448\tText\n449\tEn\n450\t\n451\tEs\n452\t\n453\tDe\n454\t\n455\tFr\n456\t\n457\tMacro\n458\tF1\n459\t\n460\t✓\n461\t✓\n462\t\n463\t✗\n464\t✗\n465\t\n466\t✗\n467\t✗\n468\t\n469\t✗\n470\t✗\n471\t\n472\t✗\n473\t✗\n474\t\n475\t0.5699\n476\t0.6239\n477\t\n478\t0.5723\n479\t0.6425\n480\t\n481\t180\n482\t213\n483\t\n484\tRoBERTa\n485\tRoBERTuito\n486\tGBERT\n487\tCamemBERT\n488\t\n489\t✗\n490\t✗\n491\t✗\n492\t✗\n493\t\n494\t✓\n495\t✗\n496\t✗\n497\t✗\n498\t\n499\t✗\n500\t✓\n501\t✗\n502\t✗\n503\t\n504\t✗\n505\t✗\n506\t✓\n507\t✗\n508\t\n509\t✗\n510\t✗\n511\t✗\n512\t✓\n513\t\n514\t0.6102\n515\t0.5751\n516\t0.5742\n517\t0.5706\n518\t\n519\t0.6235\n520\t0.5981\n521\t0.5893\n522\t0.5867\n523\t\n524\t27\n525\t138\n526\t139\n527\t138\n528\t\n529\tCCMT\n530\tCCMT\n531\tCCMT\n532\tCCMT\n533\tCCMT\n534\t\n535\t✓\n536\t✓\n537\t✓\n538\t✓\n539\t✓\n540\t\n541\t✓\n542\t✓\n543\t✓\n544\t✓\n545\t✓\n546\t\n547\t✗\n548\t✓\n549\t✗\n550\t✗\n551\t✓\n552\t\n553\t✗\n554\t✗\n555\t✓\n556\t✗\n557\t✓\n558\t\n559\t✗\n560\t✗\n561\t✗\n562\t✓\n563\t✓\n564\t\n565\t0.6812\n566\t0.6793\n567\t0.6828\n568\t0.6826\n569\t0.6812\n570\t\n571\t0.6910\n572\t0.6881\n573\t0.6924\n574\t0.6940\n575\t0.6903\n576\t\n577\t3404\n578\t30112\n579\t27714\n580\t25082\n581\t76000\n582\t\n583\tWavLM (KD from Audio + En + Fr CCMT)\n584\tWavLM (KD from Audio + En + De CCMT)\n585\t\n586\t✓\n587\t✓\n588\t\n589\t✗\n590\t✗\n591\t\n592\t✗\n593\t✗\n594\t\n595\t✗\n596\t✗\n597\t\n598\t✗\n599\t✗\n600\t\n601\t0.6393\n602\t0.6329\n603\t\n604\t0.6506\n605\t0.6474\n606\t\n607\t211\n608\t210\n609\t\n610\tModel\n611\t\n612\tAudio\n613\t\n614\tWhisper\n615\tWavLM\n616\t\n617\tAccuracy\n618\t\n619\tTime\n620\t(ms)\n621\t\n622\tmodels for KD, one that combines audio with English and French text, and one that combines audio with English and\n623\tGerman text. We use a distillation temperature of τ = 2, and a default KD weight of λ = 0.7. To test how the student\n624\treacts to the teacher’s influence, we also conduct an ablation study on λ.\n625\tEvaluation measures. We assess models in terms of accuracy rate and macro-F1 . Accuracy assigns equal importance\n626\tto each test sample, ignoring the class distribution, while macro-F1 computes the average F1 scores over all three\n627\tclasses, treating all classes as equally important.\n628\tBaselines. To compare our final unimodal (audio-only) students, we consider two strong audio-based models as\n629\tbaselines. As the first unimodal audio baseline, we consider the fine-tuned WavLM without KD. Having the same\n630\tarchitecture as our students, any performance difference between the baseline WavLM and the WavLM-based students\n631\tis due to knowledge distillation. As the second unimodal audio baseline, we fine-tune the Whisper-base encoder [38]\n632\t(74M parameters) for three-class sentiment classification on the MSP-Podcast corpus. We introduce this baseline to\n633\tbetter assess the capabilities of the WavLM architecture w.r.t. direct unimodal competitors.\n634\tMain results and ablations. In Table 2, we report the results for unimodal, multimodal and KD-based models\n635\ton the MSP-Podcast corpus [7]. Among the two audio-only baselines, WavLM obtains clearly better performance,\n636\tsurpassing Whisper by +7% in terms of accuracy. This also suggests that further improving the already strong WavLM\n637\t7\n638\t\n639\t\f0.655\n640\t\n641\tAccuracy\n642\t\n643\t0.652\n644\t\n645\tbest: 0.6506\n646\t\n647\t0.649\n648\t\n649\t0.6467\n650\t\n651\t0.6456\n652\t\n653\t0.646\n654\t0.643\n655\t\n656\t0.6431\n657\t\n658\t0.6462\n659\t\n660\t0.6462\n661\t\n662\t0.6417 0.6420\n663\t\n664\t0.640\n665\t0.637\n666\t\n667\t0.6467\n668\t\n669\tWavLM baseline (no KD, = 0)\n670\tWavLM student with KD\n671\t\n672\t0.1\n673\t\n674\t0.2\n675\t\n676\t0.3\n677\t\n678\t0.4\n679\t\n680\t0.5\n681\t\n682\t0.6\n683\t\n684\tDistillation weight\n685\t\n686\t0.7\n687\t\n688\t0.8\n689\t\n690\t0.9\n691\t\n692\tFigure 2: Accuracy rates of the WavLM student across different values for the distillation weight λ. The teacher is the CCMT based on Audio +\n693\tEn + Fr. The dashed line marks the WavLM baseline trained without KD (λ = 0). The best result is obtained at λ = 0.7.\n694\t\n695\tis not going to be easy. Taken individually, the text-only models obtain lower performance levels than the audio-based\n696\tWavLM. This is an expected phenomenon, since text-only models rely on automatically generated inputs that contain\n697\tinherent errors, thereby degrading performance. Among text-only models, RoBERTa obtains the highest performance\n698\tlevels, likely because text translations to Spanish, German and French contain additional errors introduced during\n699\tthe NMT process, which further degrades performance. Yet, an encouraging observation is that all text-only models\n700\toutperform the audio-based Whisper, which indicates that these models may still be useful in a multimodal context.\n701\tLooking at the multimodal (audio-text) CCMT variants, we observe that integrating multiple modalities leads to\n702\tsignificant performance boosts over the audio-only WavLM model. Performance gains are around +5% in absolute\n703\tpercentage points, which is quite impressive, given that all text modalities are generated via ASR and NMT. KD\n704\tfrom CCMT to WavLM is applied for the top two CCMT variants. Both WavLM students outperform the fine-tuned\n705\tWavLM baseline, suggesting that distillation is useful. Actually, the utility of KD becomes more evident when we\n706\tanalyze the computational time. While CCMT achieves significant performance gains, all CCMT variants are slower\n707\tby at least one order of magnitude than the audio-only models. In contrast, the WavLM students attain the same\n708\tinference speed as the audio-only models, since they do not require additional text-based inputs during inference.\n709\tIn summary, our empirical results indicate that generated transcripts and translations provide additional sentiment\n710\tpolarity clues that can be effectively harnessed by a multimodal model. Moreover, the results confirm that knowledge\n711\tfrom heavy multimodal models can be distilled into efficient unimodal students.\n712\tAblation of λ. In Figure 2, we present KD results with various values for λ, the hyperparameter that controls the\n713\tinfluence of the two loss components in Eq. (5). When λ = 0, the KD process is turned off, so the results correspond\n714\tto the WavLM model without KD. The student WavLM model surpasses the WavLM (no KD) baseline, when the\n715\tvalue chosen for λ ≥ 0.4. This indicates that multimodal information is generally beneficial during KD, providing\n716\tperformance gains, even when λ is not optimally configured.\n717\t\n718\t5. Conclusion\n719\tIn this work, we proposed a novel knowledge distillation framework for audio sentiment polarity classification,\n720\twhere a multimodal teacher integrates the speech signal with automatically generated text transcripts and translations\n721\tthrough a cascaded cross-modal transformer architecture, and transfers its knowledge to an efficient audio-only student. Experiments on the large-scale MSP-Podcast corpus confirmed both of our working hypotheses. First, augmenting the audio modality with generated multilingual text yielded substantial gains over the unimodal WavLM baseline,\n722\twith improvements of up to +5.89% in terms of macro-F1 and +5.15% in terms of accuracy, while our ablation study\n723\tindicated that both ASR transcripts and machine-translated texts contribute to the final performance. Second, the\n724\tmultimodal knowledge captured by the teacher was effectively distilled into the audio-only student, boosting its performance by +1.54% in terms of macro-F1 and +0.81% in terms of accuracy, without introducing any computational\n725\toverhead at inference time. Taken together, these results demonstrate that automatically generated textual modalities\n726\tcan serve as effective privileged information for training efficient audio-only sentiment classifiers.\n727\t8\n728\t\n729\t\fAcknowledgments\n730\tThis research is supported by PPC Romania via the 2025-2026 Scholarship Program.\n731\t\n732\tReferences\n733\t[1] Anilsagar, T., Syed, S.S.A., 2025. The evolution of sentiment analysis and conversational AI: Techniques applications and future research\n734\tdirections. Journal of Systems Engineering and Electronics 35, 71–82.\n735\t[2] Atmaja, B.T., Sasou, A., 2022. Sentiment analysis and emotion recognition from speech using universal speech representations. Sensors 22,\n736\t6369.\n737\t[3] Baevski, A., Zhou, Y., Mohamed, A., Auli, M., 2020. wav2vec 2.0: A framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations, in:\n738\tProceedings of NeurIPS, pp. 12449–12460.\n739\t[4] Barbieri, F., Camacho-Collados, J., Espinosa Anke, L., Neves, L., 2020. TweetEval: Unified benchmark and comparative evaluation for tweet\n740\tclassification, in: Findings of EMNLP, pp. 1644–1650.\n741\t[5] Bulkrock, O., Qusef, A., BaniMustafa, A., 2025. Sentiment Analysis of Customer Feedback and Reviews in E-Commerce Systems, in:\n742\tProceedings of ICTCS, pp. 379–385.\n743\t[6] Busso, C., Bulut, M., Lee, C.C., Kazemzadeh, A., Mower, E., Kim, S., Chang, J.N., Lee, S., Narayanan, S.S., 2008. IEMOCAP: Interactive\n744\temotional dyadic motion capture database. Language Resources and Evaluation 42, 335–359.\n745\t[7] Busso, C., Lotfian, R., Sridhar, K., Salman, A.N., Lin, W.C., Goncalves, L., Parthasarathy, S., Naini, A.R., Leem, S.G., Martinez-Lucas, L.,\n746\tet al., 2025. The MSP-Podcast Corpus. arXiv preprint arXiv:2509.09791 .\n747\t[8] Chan, B., Schweter, S., Möller, T., 2020. German’s next language model, in: Proceedings of COLING, pp. 6788–6796.\n748\t[9] Chen, S., Wang, C., Chen, Z., Wu, Y., Liu, S., Chen, Z., Li, J., Kanda, N., Yoshioka, T., Xiao, X., Wu, J., Zhou, L., Ren, S., Qian, Y., Qian, Y.,\n749\tWu, J., Z